Hi @taipingqu, can you give us some information on this -- what input image did you pass into freesurfer, for example? We never provided the "original" file for our volume, so I'm not sure what you are comparing in the screenshot above.
Thanks.

Thanks @adalca.I downloaded the original data from ADNI, the slice thickness is 1mm, the shape is approximately 256x204x240, then I preprocessed with freesurfer.After resampling the scans to 256x256x256 with freesurfer, I crop them by the following ammounts: ((48, 48), (31, 33), (3, 29)).
![20181124093858](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/35133044/48963463-ce1ad800-efcd-11e8-9e2c-2c93ba445ab8.jpg)
Add: We use files in .nii format.I compare test_vol with the npz file I generated.

Ah I see. So in the screenshot above, it is not the exact same subject, just a similar one?

In that case, perhaps it's worth just running affine registration (e.g. using ANTs) to our atlas, to make sure they're in the same space. Other than that, you should be good to go to use VoxelMorph.

Hi Adrian.Does asep.mgz generated by freesurfer also need affine registration? (such as using ANTs)
if i understand your question, yes you need to transform it using the affine matrix from the respective subject file, so that it's in the same space as the transformed subject file.
